eMeanings":[{"name":"St","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized spelling of French   St  .   Denis  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Denis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Camille, Jacques, Armand, Marcel, Andre, Pierre, Serge, Yvan, Alphonse, Edouard, Francois, Gaetane.  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Jorge, Roberto, Angel, Francisco, Joaquin, Juan, Manuel, Miguel, Ramon, Rolando.","French, Walloon, Breton, West Indian (mainly Haiti), German, Dutch, English, and Portuguese; Spanish and Galician (<b>Denís</b>): from the personal name <i>Denis</i>, Spanish and Galician <i>Denís</i>, from Latin <i>Dionysius</i> ‘(follower) of Dionysos’ (see   Dennis  ). Compare   Dennee  .","Ukrainian and Rusyn: variant transliteration of   Denys  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Philbert","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Monique.  German Kurt.","French and German (Bavaria): from the personal name <i>Philbert</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Filuberht</i> (see   Philibert  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Philibert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Fernand, Mirielle, Pascale, Pierrot.","French: from the personal name <i>Philibert</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Filuberht</i>, composed of the elements <i>fila</i> ‘much, very’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright’, which was borne by a 7th-century Christian saint, abbot of Jumièges. The spelling has been influenced by personal names of Greek origin based on <i>philein</i> ‘to love’, e.g.   Philip  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"William de St Philbert was born about 1140, in England, United Kingdom. He married Emma Unknown about 1174, in Bray, Berkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1180, in his hometown, at the age of 42."},"et":{"about 1140–about 1180":"umbes 1140–umbes 1180","1145–1180":"1145–1180","1175–1240":"1175–1240","1140–1180":"1140–1180","Abt 1175":"umbes 1175","about 1140":"umbes 1140","Abt 1174":"umbes 1174","about 1180":"umbes 1180","1145":"1145","1175":"1175","1240":"1240","1140":"1140","1180":"1180","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bray, Maidenhead, Berkshire, England":"Bray, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1140–about 1180":"noin 1140–noin 1180","1145–1180":"1145–1180","1175–1240":"1175–1240","1140–1180":"1140–1180","Abt 1175":"noin 1175","about 1140":"noin 1140","Abt 1174":"noin 1174","about 1180":"noin 1180","1145":"1145","1175":"1175","1240":"1240","1140":"1140","1180":"1180","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bray, Maidenhead, Berkshire, England":"Bray, Berkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1140–about 1180":"environ 1140–environ 1180","1145–1180":"1145–1180","1175–1240":"1175–1240","1140–1180":"1140–1180","Abt 1175":"environ 1175","about 1140":"environ 1140","Abt 1174":"environ 1174","about 1180":"environ 1180","1145":"1145","1175":"1175","1240":"1240","1140":"1140","1180":"1180","England, United Kingdom":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Bray, Maidenhead, Berkshire, England":"Bray, Berkshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"William de St Philbert est né environ 1140, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a épousé Emma Unknown environ 1174, à Bray, Berkshire, Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé environ 1180, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 42 ans."},"de":{"about 1140–about 1180":"um 1140–um 1180","1145–1180":"1145–1180","1175–1240":"1175–1240","1140–1180":"1140–1180","Abt 1175":"um 1175","about 1140":"um 1140","Abt 1174":"um 1